'''Ugayafukiaezu''' (&#40284;&#33914;&#33609;&#33914;&#19981;&#21512;&#21629;) is a [[Japan]]ese [[deity]] ([[kami]]). In [[Kojiki]] the name appears as &#22825;&#27941;&#26085;&#39640;&#26085;&#23376;&#27874;&#38480;&#24314;&#40284;&#33609;&#33894;&#19981;&#21512;&#21629; (Amatsuhitakahiko nakisatake ugayafukiaezu no mikoto), and in [[Nihonshoki]] &#24422;&#27874;&#28722;&#27494;&#40469;&#40383;&#33609;&#33914;&#19981;&#21512;&#23562; (Hikonagisatake ugayafukiaezu no mikoto).

Ugayafukiaezu was a child of [[Hoori]] and the daughter of the [[Neptune]] [[Toyotamabina]]. Although Toyotamabina became pregnant at ([[Ryugu]]), the sea shrine, she rose to the land, for she thought that she ought not to bear the child of the Tenjin (heaven's god) in the sea. Hoori and Toyotamabina tried to build a house for delivering in the beach, but while they were finishing roofing the house with the feather of cormorant instead of saw grass, Toyotamabina began labor. So the child was named Ugayafukiaezu (lit. the roofing cormorant alternative to saw grass was not in time). In delivering she said to Hoori "a person in other countries goes back to the original form when delivering a child. Because I think I too am going back to the original form, do not look at the house no matter what, while I am delivering." However, Hoori looked in the house and saw [[Yahirowani]] (shark), her original form, so he ran away. Toyotamabina felt shameful and returned to the sea, leaving her newborn child behind and sending her younger sister [[Tamayoribina]] instead. While helding a grudge against him, Toyotamabina missed Hoori as she loved him, so she communicated with him via her sister.

Later, Ugayafukiaezu got married with Tamayoribina, who rose him, and they had four children [[Itsuse]], [[Inahi]], [[Mikenu]] and [[Wakemikenu]]. Mikenu traveled to [[Tokoyo]] (lit. the normal world; some point that it is afterworld), and Inahi went to the ocean where his (her?) mother is. Wakamikenu, the youngest, became [[Emperor Jinmu of Japan|Emperor Jinmu]] afterward.

